  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Strengthening Disaster Preparedness and Response Systems in Lesotho</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The project aims to enhance capacity of Government in Early Warning and Early Action (EW/EA) and shock responsive social protection system in order to mitigate and respond to disaster risks and reduce the vulnerability of the disaster-affected communities, especially women, children and other vulnerable populations. The project aims to achieve the following four results;i) Integrated and functional Early Warning Systems are in place to address shocks: This result aims at strengthening an integrated and functional EW system; develop scalability framework and trigger mechanism for EA, and building capacity of relevant institutions to prepare for and respond to disasters such as drought, snow and floods.ii) Relevant stakeholders have access to updated National Information System for Social Assistance in normal and emergency situations: This result aims to ensure access to NISSA data during emergencies through a NISSA portal and development of a methodology for updating NISSA data using community structures.iii) Disaster Management and Social protection leadership of relevant institutions have capacity to manage shocks efficiently and effectively: To achieve this result, three interventions will be implemented: Development of a strategy framework for shock responsive social protection, Strengthen advocacy towards Early Warning /Early action and shock responsive social protection, and utilization of NISSA; Strengthen harmonized coordination mechanism at National and subnational levels for the effective management of shock responsive social protection systems.iv) Disaster management and social protection leadership of relevant institutions have capacity to manage shocks efficiently and effectively by updating the existing Lesotho Multi-Hazard contingency plan, activating the crisis modifier if thresholds are surpassed and conduct a process evaluation of the activation.</narrative>
  </description>
